results.notes: Datos de Yopal, registrado en Bosque Seco Tropical (temporada de lluvia). Precipitación mínima de 15 – 25 mm en los meses de enero y diciembre, Precipitación máxima 350 mm y 300 mm en los meses de mayo, junio y julio. con menos de 60 mm de lluvia en el mes más seco y precipitación anual superior a 1270 mm. Cuenta con valores mínimos de humedad relativa a inicio del año (65%), y valores más altos en junio, julio, agosto y septiembre (90-85%). cuenta con una altura sobre el nivel del mar entre 0 y 1000 m, una pluviosidad entre 2000 y 4000 mm y temperatura promedio mayor de 24 °C, con amplitud de temperatura máxima de 8 °C, como se referencia en DANE. Los máximos valores de temperatura no sobrepasan los 36 °C y los mínimos valores no logran bajar los 19 °C que se presentan en febrero y en julio, respectivamente. Temperatura media anual mayor de 20 °C, con una estación seca y una lluviosa bien definidas. (Bustamante et al., 2017; DANE, 1999; Castro y Sosa, 2017). Son comunes plantas representativas como Yarumo (Cecropia peltata), Jobo (Spondias mombin), Cedro (Cedrela odorata), Nauno (Albizzia guachepele), Cañafistol (Cassia moschata), Flor blanco (Tabebuia orinocensis), Uña de gato (Cynodon dactylon), entre otras.

results.notes:
On the ground; 2-3 needle pines mixed with oak.
Gills appear to be free, although I wonder if this may be due to the edges having broken away from the stipe. Rounded inner edged seem to suggest otherwise (free).
Spores globose/subglobose, 7-8 microns, seemingly smooth; amyloid. Print white.
Fruit body was old and deteriorating. This does not bring to my mind any species of Amanita, although the material is old and perhaps the macro-traits are eroded/deformed due to occasionally subfreezing temperatures. In past years I have seen specimens representing the A. lavendula group very late in the season. Maybe the basal bulb had rotted in-situ? Nothing else comes to mind, except perhaps Mycena. But neither the fruit body nor the spores remind me of this genus.
Material was not found in a condition worthy of preservation.

Specimen growing on base of palm frond.

Thallus endophloedal, pale yellowish; photobiont chlorococcoid/trentepolhioid? (cells solitary or in clumps, yellowish-green, round to ovoid, diam 8.8 mm mean, range 6.3-13.0 mm), in scattered clumps within substrate and below apothecia. Hexagonal, hyaline crystals present; K-, KC-, UV-, I+ orange, PD- (may be independent of fungus; algae reported as often strongly associated w/ P. atrata).
Apothecia growing on exposed phloem fibers, scattered, lecideine, excipular rim prominent, cracked, sessile, constricted at base; diam. 0.6 mm mean, range 0.4-1.0 mm) Disk black, not pruinose, flat to somewhat convex.
Exciple continuous below hypothecium, thickness 40 um lateral, up to 105 um below.
Epithecium blue-black, 25 um thick, K+ greenish; Hymenium hyaline, not inspersed, 155 um high; paraphyses moniliform, branched near tips, colored tips conglutinate and forming a thick epithecium; K-, I and K/I+ pale blue turning orange; Subhymenium hyaline, 20 um wide, K-, I-, K/I-; Hypothecium grayish or hyaline, 40 um wide, K+ green, I-, K/I-.
Asci height 99 um mean, range 85-109 um; width 15 um mean, range 13-15.5 um, 8-spored, tip I- or I+ pale blue, K/I- or + pale blue, tholus I-, K/I-.
Ascospores hyaline, 8-10-celled, curved or straight, tapered at one end; locules round; K/I+ orange; 39.0-46.8 × 7.8 um
Pycnidia (from separate fungus?) abundant, scattered, most abundant near apothecia, sessile, black, diam 58 mm, range 26-112 mm; conidia simple, hyaline, elongate, ~0.5-1 um.

results.notes:
A single young fruiting body beneath 2nd growth Douglas fir. Fibrillose, broadly conical cap, reddish cast(more silky than spiny), smooth/round slightly scurry stipe(bright azurescent blue staining mid stem to base). Not staining greenish but solid azurescent blue. Harvested/dried this specimen after spore printing the cap directly on a glass slide for microscopy. Images of spore micro included in this observation.
Spores: ellipsoid, smooth, metallic, shiny/reflective, very large.

COMPARISON: the very final image included in this observation is of both Inosperma maximum and Inosperma calamistratum side by side in my left hand to show macroscopic differences. Inosperma maximum on left(palm) with a more broadly conical cap, smoother long fibers on cap(silkier), smoother rounder stem staining azurescent blue.
I. calamistratum (posed on right) on my fingers is densely scaly from top to bottom(like very young Pholiota squarrosa) with rounded caps(deeply incurved margins) and aquamarine/green staining stem base(not pure blue). In addition to the macroscopic differences, the spores of Inosperma maximum are far larger, shiny/reflective/metallic and ellipsoid- where Inosperma calamistratum are smaller, curved(slightly sausage like) and dull.

results.notes:
Growing on a large hardwood log. C du Q says that I. benzoinum is known to grow on beech, and the log this was growing on may be beech. Most likely this is I. resinosum. I don’t recall ever finding an ischnoderma fruit body on conifer wood, which suggests that I. benzoinum is uncommon in my area.

The thing that’s interesting about Ischnoderma is how much the fruit body changes in appearance from the immature to a post mature stage. Young Ischnoderma has pores so small they are virtually invisible to the naked eye. Mature versions usually feature small roundish pores visible to the naked eye. The fruit body seen here (mature to post mature) has pores that are about 4 per mm. Except that some of the walls of the tubes have apparently dried out and broke apart causing several pores to merge into slotlike openings.

Context not spongy, but soft enough to tear apart with only minor effort.

KOH instantly black on cap surface and on context just below the surface, although the latter is likely due to the KOH reacting on the surface and then bleeding into to context (see photo). KOH brown on inner context and light brown on tubes.

Spores cylindric to slightly curved, 5.5-7 × 1.5-2.

Growing on the ground ~ 1850 ft.
Caps dry, up to 3.7 cm across surface.
No distinctive odor.
Gills brownish but not solid.
Stipe hollow.
Spore print white and spores not amyloid.
Spores ~ 7.0-8.8 X 4.0-4.8 microns, elongate subamygdaliform and smooth. Qavg = 1.83.
